The Arty MPW Tester is a simple expansion board compatible with Digilent Arty A7 development kit. This board connects IO signals from the Xilinx Artix FPGA located on the Arty board to an open hardware [Caravel](https://github.com/efabless/caravel_board) breakout board. The Caravel breakout board allows testing ASIC designs prepared for Multi Project Wafer (MPW) shuttles and fabricated with the SkyWater Process Design Kit (PDKs).

You can learn more about the OpenMPW Shuttle Program by visiting this [link](https://efabless.com/open_shuttle_program).

The Arty MPW Tester board routes the interfaces from Caravel and provides the necessary power buses.

nodes.description: This board targets a single DDR5 DRAM IC. It is compatible with the LPDDR4 Test Board and allows custom DRAM controller development and testing targeting single DDR5 ICs using the mature [LPDDR4 test platform](https://github.com/antmicro/lpddr4-test-board). The board is designed to target the Micron [MT60B2G8HB-48B:A](https://www.farnell.com/datasheets/3704816.pdf) 16Gb DRAM. It can be connected to a test board to simulate Rowhammer attacks on the embedded memory module.

An experimental platform for development of RAM controllers supporting RDIMM DDR4 RAM modules commonly used in data centers, built around the Xilinx Kintex-7 FPGA.

This hardware platform is used in Antmicro's and Google's [Rowhammer testing framework](https://github.com/antmicro/litex-rowhammer-tester) which can be used to perform (and potentially mitigate) Rowhammer-type attacks on DRAM memories. You can learn more about Rowhammer and our work towards mitigating it in a [Google Open Source blog note](https://opensource.googleblog.com/2021/11/Open%20source%20DDR%20controller%20framework%20for%20mitigating%20Rowhammer.html) describing a related platform.

You can read more about this board in this [Antmicro blog note](https://antmicro.com/blog/2021/12/open-source-data-center-rowhammer-tester/).

This board allows you to develop and customize RAM controllers to implement countermeasures against Rowhammer attacks and to experiment with DIMM DDR5 RAM modules used in data centers. The board contains a Xilinx Kintex-7 series FPGA in a 676-BGA package and has a single USB 2.0 interface that provides access to a 4-channel FTDI transceiver that allows reconfiguration of the FPGA and access to the debug console.

The on-board configuration flash can store the bitstream that is loaded at startup. In addition, a 1Gb Ethernet interface is provided to access the DDR5 Tester over the local network infrastructure. The DDR5 Tester includes on-board 64Mb HyperRAM for storing critical runtime data.

You can learn more about the DDR5 Tester in this [Antmicro blog note](https://antmicro.com/blog/2022/08/extending-the-open-source-rowhammer-testing-framework-to-ddr5/).

nodes.description:
Open source baseboard supporting the NVIDIA Jetson Nano, Xavier NX, and TX2 NX SoMs.

The board will let you take advantage of the processing power the Jetson Nano offers in numerous possible ways by exposing several interfaces, e.g. the board can be interfaced with MIPI CSI-2 video devices through a unified Flexible Flat Cable (FFC) connector, supporting up to 4 sensors in a 2-lane configuration or 3 sensors in a 4-lane configuration.

Read more about the Jetson Nano Baseboard on [Antmicro’s blog](https://antmicro.com/blog/2020/10/open-jetson-nano-xavier-baseboard-available-for-purchase/).

World's first open-source baseboard supporting NVIDIA Jetson Orin Nano and Jetson Orin NX System-on-Modules, and successor to the greatly popular [Jetson Nano Baseboard](https://opensource.antmicro.com/projects/jetson-nano-baseboard).

The board will help you harness Orin NX's performance while offering plenty of flexibility - it can be powered using three possible sources (PoE included), features an array of interfaces, and offers compatibility with a range of video accessories developed by Antmicro (e.g. adapters for [FRAMOS](https://github.com/antmicro/framos-csi-adapter) and [Allied Vision](https://github.com/antmicro/alvium-flexible-csi-adapter) cameras). All that while fitting within a 120 x 60 mm footprint.

Read more about the Jetson Orin Baseboard on [Antmicro's blog](https://antmicro.com/blog/2022/12/baseboard-for-nvidia-jetson-orin/).

Expansion board compatible with [Jetson Orin Baseboard](https://github.com/antmicro/jetson-orin-baseboard).
It ncludes a MicroSD card slot and an M.2 (key-M) slot intended for connecting additional storage solutions to the Jetson Orin Baseboard.
The M.2 slot supports 2280 and 2242 M.2 NVMe discs.

The Lotus Elise chassis-based Tesla Roadster, the first serial production, all-electric car to use lithium-ion battery cells, debuted in 2008, offering unprecedented travel range. The open source release of some of the assets constituting the hardware and software of the Roadster, including the Vehicle Management System, the Vehicle Display System and the Battery Management System, opened the possibility of employing tools such as Renode and the hardware library to visualize, analyze and simulate the released components.

The Battery Management Board in the Tesla Roadster is responsible for monitoring and managing the performance of the lithium-ion battery cells that power the vehicle. It plays a pivotal role in maintaining the balance and health of the battery pack, which is essential for the vehicle's overall efficiency and safety. It's managed by the Vehicle Management System.

nodes.category: Devices/Tesla Roadster Vehicle Display System board
nodes.description: The Tesla Roadster Vehicle Display System Board is a crucial component of the vehicle's user interface, responsible for managing the digital displays and providing drivers with vital information and controls. The VDS is designed to drive the vehicle's digital dashboard and infotainment displays, delivering real-time data, navigation, multimedia, and vehicle controls to the driver and passengers. It's managed by the Vehicle Management System.

The Vehicle Management System (VMS) in the Tesla Roadster is a sophisticated system designed to monitor, control, and optimize the vehicle's performance and safety. It manages and communicates with the Battery Management System (BMS) for managing the lithium-ion battery pack, the Power Electronics Module (PEM) for controlling power flow between the battery and motor, the Vehicle Display System (VDS) for managing the digital displays, and the Motor Control System for torque and speed management. Additionally, the VMS provides telemetry and diagnostics for real-time data and remote support, a user interface for driver interaction, and safety systems for collision detection and airbag deployment. The VMS firmware is supported in the Renode simulation framework.
